Analysis.name: Live birth (or ongoing pregnancy) – all studies
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc: "The participants were divided into two groups using simple (1:1) randomization. The patients were randomly assigned the numbers one to fifty and those with an even number were assigned to the control group and those with an odd number were assigned to the treatment group". Although the patients were randomly assigned the numbers, their assignment to the group was not completely random. The investigators might have decided which numbers (odd or even) to assign to each group (control or treatment). In addition, no method for the concealment of the allocated numbers is described.
Bias.due.to.deviations.from.intended.int: Though the authors did not provide extensive information on the interventions, we assume that this sham intervention assisted in the blinding of the participants. If such measures had been taken, they could have prevented the carers from being aware of the participants' assigned intervention.
Bias.due.to.missing.outcome.data.support: Although the trial authors analyzed all the outcomes on an intention-to-treat basis, they did not provide data on the follow-up of the participants. Therefore, we are not aware of whether there is missing data on participants.
Bias.in.measurement.of.the.outcome.suppo: Live birth was defined and measured properly.
Bias.in.selection.of.the.reported.result: We have some concerns since there is no prespecified analysis plan for the outcome. However, the numerical result has likely not been influenced by multiple eligible measurements or analyses.
Overall.bias.support: The study is judged at a high risk of bias for the outcome of live birth since two domains were judged at a high risk of bias.

Analysis.name: Live birth (or ongoing pregnancy) – all studies
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc: We have some concerns considering that there is no information on either the allocation sequence generation or the allocation concealment except for the term "randomized".
Bias.due.to.deviations.from.intended.int: We have some concerns considering that the carers were most likely aware of the participants' assigned intervention and that we found a minor deviation from the protocol regarding the centrifugation of blood for the preparation of PRP, yet with an unlikely effect on the outcome.
Bias.due.to.missing.outcome.data.support: The authors reported that all patients were followed up and that there were no missing data on the pregnancy outcomes.
Bias.in.selection.of.the.reported.result: Studying the ongoing pregnancy rates of the groups was not an intention of the authors at the protocol stage, since its measurement was not specified a priori. Since the outcome is not properly defined, the numerical results could have been affected if the women of the two groups were monitored for ongoing pregnancy at different time points.
Overall.bias.support: Regarding the outcome of Live birth the study was judged at a high risk of bias since one domain was judged at a high risk of bias.

Analysis.name: Live birth (or ongoing pregnancy) – all studies
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc: The allocation sequence generation and concealment are properly described.
Bias.due.to.deviations.from.intended.int: Although the participants and their carers might have been aware of the assigned interventions, we observed no deviations from the interventions that had been intended at the protocol stage. The outcomes were also analyzed on an intention-to-treat basis.
Bias.due.to.missing.outcome.data.support: As per the CONSORT flow diagram of the study, there seems to have been no loss to follow-up and, therefore, no missing outcome data.
Bias.in.measurement.of.the.outcome.suppo: Due to the nature and definition of the outcome, it is unlikely that this was ascertained in a different way between the two groups. The outcome assessors were also blinded to the interventions received by study participants as the participants were coded.
Bias.in.selection.of.the.reported.result: Live birth was intented to be investigated and was defined in the same way at protocol stage.
Overall.bias.support: All domains were judged as of low risk of bias.

Analysis.name: Live birth (or ongoing pregnancy) – all studies
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc: The lack of allocation concealment primarily led to a judgment of "some concerns".
Bias.due.to.deviations.from.intended.int: We have some concerns considering that the authors likely provided no description of the intended interventions at the protocol stage.
Bias.due.to.missing.outcome.data.support: The authors reported that all patients were followed up and that there were no missing data on the pregnancy outcomes.
Bias.in.measurement.of.the.outcome.suppo: Ongoing pregnancy was defined and (likely) measured properly.
Bias.in.selection.of.the.reported.result: We have some concerns since there is no prespecified analysis plan for the outcome. However, the numerical result has likely not been influenced by multiple eligible measurements or analyses.
Overall.bias.support: The study is judged at a high risk of bias for the outcome of ongoing pregnancy since three domains were judged as of "some concerns".

Analysis.name: Live birth (or ongoing pregnancy) – all studies
Bias.due.to.deviations.from.intended.int: The intrauterine injection of PRP was compared to the insertion of the catheter without injection or any further mechanical action. Although the interventions were not thoroughly described at the protocol stage, we found no significant deviations from the initially intended interventions. However, it seems that the protocol was registered retrospectively; so there is no actual information on the intended interventions.
Bias.due.to.missing.outcome.data.support: The authors excluded participants after their random allocation for reasons such as ineligible age or BMI. These participants should have been excluded before the initial enrollment to the study. There is no analysis accounting for the potential bias that may have arisen from the missing data. We found unexpected reasons for exclusion after randomization. Many more patients were excluded/lost to follow-up from the control group.
Bias.in.measurement.of.the.outcome.suppo: The outcome of ongoing pregnancy was defined and likely measured properly.
Bias.in.selection.of.the.reported.result: Studying the ongoing pregnancy rates of the groups was not an intention of the authors at the protocol stage, since its measurement was not specified a priori.
Overall.bias.support: The study is judged at a high risk of bias for the outcome of ongoing pregnancy, since at least one domain was judged at a high risk of bias.

Analysis.name: Live birth – sensitivity analysis (risk ratio)
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc: No information on the allocation sequence generation or concealment. Fifty-six patients were allocated to the PRP while 76 were allocated to the G-CSF group. That is far from the probably intended 1:1 allocation ratio.

Analysis.name: Miscarriage – sensitivity analysis (risk ratio)
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc: No information on the allocation sequence generation or concealment. Fifty-six patients were allocated to the PRP while 76 were allocated to the G-CSF group. That is far from the probably intended 1:1 allocation ratio.

Analysis.name: Ongoing pregnancy – sensitivity analysis (risk ratio)
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc: We have some concerns considering that there is no information on either the allocation sequence generation or the allocation concealment except for the term "randomized".
Bias.due.to.deviations.from.intended.int: We have some concerns since we found no registered protocol for this trial; hence, we cannot conclude whether deviations from the intended interventions occurred.
Bias.due.to.missing.outcome.data.support: Despite an initial enrollment of 86 participants, only 73 participants completed the study up to the point of oocyte retrieval and data on the outcomes was provided for 21 of them. The reasons for that were not described. There were no analyses accounting for the missing data.
Bias.in.measurement.of.the.outcome.suppo: Although the outcome of ongoing pregnancy was not defined, it is less likely that it was measured inappropriately in practice.
Bias.in.selection.of.the.reported.result: We cannot be aware whether studying the ongoing pregnancy rates of the groups was an intention of the authors at the protocol stage. Since the outcome is not properly defined, the numerical results could have been affected if the women of the two groups were monitored for ongoing pregnancy at different time points.
Overall.bias.support: The study is judged at a high risk of bias for the outcome of ongoing pregnancy, since at least one domain was judged at a high risk of bias.
